    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what the text says to what it means — tracing Jeremiah's authorial intent within the historical context of the late seventh and early sixth centuries BC, reading the chapter's argument in its canonical setting, and attending to how its individual parts serve one theological whole. The movements below follow the chapter's pericope structure: the Carchemish oracle, the theological centerpiece (the Day of the LORD), the second oracle of invasion, and the closing promise to Jacob.",
