        "body": "The superscription of 46:1-2 is one of the most precisely dated prophetic texts in the Old Testament: fourth year of Jehoiakim, 605 BC, Battle of Carchemish. Jeremiah was already three decades into his ministry when this oracle came. The Battle of Carchemish was the ancient Near East's tectonic event — it ended the Assyrian imperial remnant, shattered Egyptian power north of Sinai, and handed the entire Fertile Crescent to Babylon. Pharaoh Neco II, who had already killed Josiah at Megiddo (2 Kings 23:29) and installed Jehoiakim as a tribute king, was routed so completely that 2 Kings 24:7 records: 'The king of Egypt did not come out of his land again.' The oracle does not predict Carchemish; it interprets it — showing God's people what the battle means.\n\nThe mock battle-summons of 46:3-4 is built on the literary device of *dramatic irony*: the reader knows from verse 2 that Egypt has already been defeated; the summons to deploy shields and polish spears is therefore already futile as it is being issued. Verse 5 pulls back the curtain mid-deployment: 'Why have I seen it? They are terrified.' The *why* (*maddua*) is a rhetorical shudder — the prophet looking on the scene and registering cognitive dissonance between Egypt's formidable preparation (vv.3-4) and the actual reality on the ground (v.5). The effect is to show that human preparation, however thorough, cannot override a divine verdict already rendered.\n\nThe phrase 'terror is on every side' (*magor missaviv*, 46:5) is a signature phrase of Jeremiah — it appears six times in the book (6:25; 20:3, 4, 10; 46:5; 49:29). It is the name Jeremiah gave to his persecutor Pashur (20:3), the phrase his enemies threw back at him (20:10), and here the description of Egypt's experience. Egypt inflicted terror on Israel's ancestors in the Exodus; now Egypt experiences what it once dispensed. The ironic reversal is theological, not merely poetic.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Magor missaviv* — 'terror on every side' — is Jeremiah's distinctive phrase, a kind of theological trademark. *Gibbor* (mighty man, warrior) appears four times in vv.5-12; each appearance is paired with a verb of collapse (*chathat* = be shattered; *kashal* = stumble; *naphal* = fall). The grammatical pressure on *gibbor* is relentless: the word for champion is surrounded by words for failure."
