        "body": "The second oracle (46:13-26) moves beyond the battlefield memory of Carchemish to a future invasion of Egypt itself. Historically, Nebuchadnezzar campaigned against Egypt around 568-567 BC (confirmed by the Babylonian Chronicle fragments and by Ezekiel 29:19-20, where Yahweh explicitly grants Egypt to Nebuchadnezzar as wages for his service at Tyre). Jeremiah's oracle is thus predictive prophecy that was subsequently verified — a pattern consistent with Deuteronomy 18:21-22's test of genuine prophecy.\n\nThe oracle's literary texture is richer than the first, deploying four distinct animal metaphors to characterize Egypt's humiliation. Egypt is a 'beautiful heifer' (*eglah yephehphiyyah*, v.20) — attractive, well-fed, prized — into which a horsefly (*qerets*) from the north buzzes, ruinous and unstoppable. Egypt's mercenaries are 'fattened calves' (*egel marbeq*, v.21) who flee when the crisis arrives — hired soldiers whose loyalty lasts exactly as long as their comfort. The retreating Egyptian army 'moves along like a serpent' (*nachash*, v.22) — hissing but slithering away, avoiding confrontation. And the Babylonian invaders are like 'woodcutters with axes' (v.22) felling Egypt's 'forest' (v.23) — systematic, thorough, irreversible. The forest metaphor for national power is attested in Isaiah 10:18-19 for Assyria; Jeremiah applies it to Egypt. A forest cleared by foresters does not regenerate quickly.\n\nVerse 25 marks a decisive escalation: Yahweh names Himself the agent ('Behold, I am going to punish') and names the defendants: Amon of Thebes, Pharaoh, Egypt, her gods, her kings, and all who trust in Pharaoh. The inclusion of Amon (*No*, the sacred name for Thebes as the city of Amon) is theologically pointed. Amon was Egypt's chief deity — the king of the gods in the Egyptian pantheon, the divine patron of the pharaohs. Isaiah 19:1 envisions 'the LORD riding on a swift cloud' into Egypt and the idols trembling before Him; Jeremiah 46:25 makes the prosecution explicit. Egypt's divine infrastructure is as liable to divine judgment as its military infrastructure. This is the classic OAN theological claim: the LORD of Israel is not a regional deity but the sovereign of all nations, and the gods of the nations are accountable to Him.\n\nThe brief promise of verse 26b — Egypt will be inhabited again 'as in days of old' — is debated among commentators. Some read it as a post-exilic historical restoration (Ezekiel 29:13-16 parallels, limiting Egypt's recovery to a 'lowly kingdom'). The theological point is that judgment against nations is bounded; Yahweh's purpose for Egypt is not its permanent obliteration but its humbling. Egypt's restoration is real but limited — a 'lowly kingdom' that no longer seduces Israel into false confidence (Ezekiel 29:16). The contrast with Jacob's full restoration in 46:27-28 is the chapter's final argument.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qerets* (horsefly, gadfly, v.20) — a rare word appearing only here in the Hebrew Bible, suggesting a deliberate choice for maximum irony: Egypt the heifer is not attacked by a lion or eagle (imperial symbols) but by an insect. *Paqad* (punish, v.25) is the same root used for Yahweh's 'visiting' or 'accounting' — it carries the sense of a reckoning that has been held in reserve and now arrives."
