        "excerpt": "But as for you, O Jacob My servant, do not fear, nor be dismayed, O Israel! For, see, I am going to save you from afar.",
        "body": "Structurally, 46:27-28 belongs to Jeremiah's Book of Consolation (chapters 30-33) in its theology, though it appears here appended to the Oracle Against Egypt. An almost verbatim parallel exists in Jeremiah 30:10-11. The repetition is not redundancy; it is an embedded comfort address that appears at strategic points in the book wherever the threat of overwhelming foreign power is most acute. The placement here — immediately after twenty-four verses of Egypt's collapse — is interpretively decisive. The most powerful nation of that world has just been shown to be helpless before Yahweh; the question for the exiled, scattered, apparently abandoned people of God is implicit: 'Then what about us?' The answer comes in the form of a covenant address that uses every available marker of divine intimacy.\n\nThe address 'Jacob My servant' (*eved*) is the most concentrated covenant term in the Hebrew Bible's vocabulary of relationship. Abraham, Moses, David, and the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 42-53 are all *eved Yahweh*. The designation simultaneously implies ownership ('Mine'), function ('you serve a purpose'), and protection ('I bear responsibility for you'). The double address — 'Jacob' and 'Israel' — invokes both the pre-covenantal patriarch and the covenant name God gave him at Peniel (Genesis 32:28), encompassing both the struggling human and the one who prevailed with God. Both dimensions of Israel's identity are gathered into the promise.\n\nThe five elements of the promise in verse 27 are cumulative: (1) 'I am going to save you from afar' — distance is no barrier to divine rescue; (2) 'your descendants from the land of their captivity' — the promise extends to the next generation, covering temporal depth; (3) 'Jacob will return' — the return is not contingent on Jacob's worthiness but on Yahweh's announced intention; (4) 'undisturbed' (*shaqat*, at rest, quiet) — the quality of the return is peace, not merely survival; (5) 'with no one making him tremble' — the reversal of the exile's anxiety is complete. The *charad* (tremble, be afraid) that ended verse 27 is the same root used for the trembling terror Egypt's warriors experienced (comparable to *magor*, v.5); Jacob's future is the precise opposite of Egypt's present.\n\nVerse 28 holds in careful balance what must not be separated: God will make a full end of the nations (the nations are instruments, not heirs) but will not make a full end of Jacob (the heir is preserved through the discipline). The discipline itself — 'I will correct you properly' (*yasar bemishpat*) — uses the Deuteronomic vocabulary of fatherly instruction (Deuteronomy 8:5: 'as a man disciplines his son, so the LORD your God disciplines you'). John Calvin observed on this verse that God's covenant people are simultaneously under the guarantee of His promise and the experience of His chastening — neither cancels the other. D. A. Carson's treatment of divine sovereignty and human responsibility in the prophetic literature reinforces the same point: the scattered exiles are not outside God's plan; they are inside His pedagogical purpose.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaqat* (undisturbed, at quiet rest, v.27) and *shaan* (ease, security, v.27) together paint the Sabbath-like peace of the restoration. *Yasar* (correct, discipline, v.28) is the parental instruction word of Proverbs (3:11-12; 13:24) and Deuteronomy 8:5; it implies relationship, not merely punishment. *Mishpat* (properly, justly) here anchors the discipline in covenant justice rather than arbitrary severity — God's correction is measured, purposeful, and righteous."
